1!a         // set a to 1
a?          // returns a

a?>        // prints value of a

10>        // prints 10

a?b        // if a nonzero, b

a?(a>)     // if a nonzero , print a



Syntax

a b     => if a is nonzero, then evaluate b
a.b 	=> concatenate a and b
a=b 	=> evaluate to a, if a == b
a,b     => evaluate a, then b
a?      => get value of a
a!b     => set b to value of a, returns b

INVARIANT 1
	a!b,b?

will always have value of a

a?b      => while a, evaluate b

Note. 
Let a be variable.

Then
a?b
will evaluate to
[value of a] b,

so it's an 'if'.

When a is a constant, this makes an infinite loop for any nonzero value!

To make an infinite loop with variable a, you must do

a??b - while value of a is nonzero, evaluate b

a! - output a
!a - input a


!?a - do a while input nonzero

==========================
ECHO PROGRAM

(!a)?(a!)


! - store first operand to second operand


